Devon, England":"Arlington, Devon, England",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hatch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hatch (Bedfordshire, Devon, Hampshire, Somerset, Wiltshire), Hacche in South Molton (Devon), or else a topographic name from residence near a hatch, a gate leading to a forest or sometimes a sluice-gate, from Middle English <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>hæcce</i>, Kentish Old English <i>hec(c)</i>). This name has been in Ireland since the 17th century, associated with County Meath and the nearby part of Louth."],"variants":[{"name":"Hedge","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a hedge or enclosure, from Middle English <i>hegge</i> ‘hedge, fence’. In the early Middle Ages, hedges were not merely dividers between fields, but had an important defensive function when planted around a settlement or enclosure.","English: probably also a variant of   Hatch  , with voicing of the final consonant.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Hecke  ."]},{"name":"Hatcher","meanings":["English (southern): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate, from Middle English <i>haccher(e)</i>, a derivative of <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’. This normally denoted a gate marking the entrance to a forest or other enclosed piece of land, sometimes a floodgate or sluice-gate. Compare   Hatch  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Hatch was born in 1350, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Jeffery de Hatche, was 30 and his mother, Elizabeth Hecche, was 30. He married Jane Worlington about 1380, in Beaford, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1420, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1350–1420":"1350–1420","1364–1418":"1364–1418","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1368–1404":"1368–1404","1399–Male":"1399–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","about 1380":"umbes 1380","6 February 1404":"6. veebruar 1404","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1404":"1404","1368":"1368","Abt 1399":"umbes 1399","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1364":"1364","before 1340":"enne 1340","1418":"1418","Arlington, Devon, England":"Arlington, Devon, England",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1350–1420":"1350–1420","1364–1418":"1364–1418","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","1352–Female":"1352–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1368–1404":"1368–1404","1399–Male":"1399–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","about 1380":"noin 1380","6 February 1404":"6. helmikuuta 1404","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1404":"1404","1368":"1368","Abt 1399":"noin 1399","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1364":"1364","before 1340":"ennen vuotta 1340",